C%20on%20average%2C%20almost%20seven%20hours%20a%20day%20on%20leisure%20and%20sports%2C%20with%20four%20of%20those%20hours%20spent%20watching%20TV.%20Adults%2025%20to%2054%2C%20on%20the%20other%20hand%2C%20averaged%20about%20four%20hours%20of%20leisure%20time%20and%20about%20two%20hours%20watching%20TV.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3ESpending%20your%20twilight%20years%20lying%20around%20might%20sound%20ideal%20%E2%80%94%20after%20all%2C%20everyone%20deserves%20a%20chance%20to%20relax%20after%20decades%20of%20working.%20But%20research%20suggests%20a%20life%20of%20pure%20leisure%20doesn't%20make%20you%20happier%20or%20healthier.%20About%20a%20third%20of%20American%20adults%20have%20said%20they%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.businessinsider.com%2Fworried-retirement-will-leave-me-without-a-sense-of-purpose-2024-11%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3Estruggled%20in%20transitioning%20to%20a%20life%3C%2Fa%3E%20without%20work%2C%20and%20sedentary%20lifestyles%20are%20associated%20with%20earlier%20death.%20People%20are%20living%20about%2015%20years%20longer%20than%20they%20did%20a%20hundred%20years%20ago%2C%20which%20means%20we%20have%20many%20more%20years%20to%20spend%20in%20retirement.%20While%20there's%20much%20hand-wringing%20over%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.businessinsider.com%2Fgen-x-retirement-savings-crisis-401k-kids-parents-work-caregiving-2024-12%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3Ehow%20to%20save%20up%20enough%20money%3C%2Fa%3E%20to%20enjoy%20those%20work-free%20years%2C%20much%20less%20discussed%20is%20%3Cem%3Ehow%3C%2Fem%3E%20we%20should%20spend%20those%20years.%20More%20and%20more%20research%20is%20finding%20that%20both%20physical%20and%20social%20activity%20are%20crucial%20for%20well-being%20in%20old%20age%20%E2%80%94%20they%20keep%20people%20happier%20and%20living%20longer.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EBut%20that's%20not%20what%20most%20people%20are%20doing.%20Americans%20are%20doing%20retirement%20all%20wrong.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Chr%3E%3Cp%3EThe%20concept%20of%20retirement%20as%20we%20know%20it%20came%20from%20German%20Chancellor%20Otto%20von%20Bismarck%2C%20who%20in%201889%20designed%20a%20social%20insurance%20program%20compelling%20the%20government%20to%20care%20for%20people%20who%20couldn't%20work%20because%20of%20age%20or%20disability.%20When%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.businessinsider.com%2Funretired-boomer-works-supplement-social-security-payments-financially-helps-children-2024-11%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3ESocial%20Security%3C%2Fa%3E%20was%20established%20in%20the%20US%20in%201935%2C%20the%20retirement%20age%20was%20set%20at%2065%2C%20though%20the%20average%20life%20expectancy%20was%20about%2060%20years.%20The%20norm%20was%20for%20people%20to%20work%20until%20they%20could%20not%20work%20anymore.%20Today%20the%20average%20life%20expectancy%20is%20about%2077%2C%20and%20the%20age%20you%20can%20start%20receiving%20full%20Social%20Security%20benefits%20is%20either%2066%20or%2067%2C%20depending%20on%20when%20you%20were%20born.%20We're%20working%20longer%20and%20living%20longer.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EThat%20has%20created%20two%20problems%3A%20People%20need%20to%20figure%20out%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.businessinsider.com%2Fboomers-not-enough-retirement-savings-gen-z-millennials-eldercare-2024-1%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3Ehow%20to%20pay%20for%20a%20longer%20retirement%3C%2Fa%3E%20and%20how%20to%20spend%20their%20time.%20Anqi%20Chen%2C%20a%20senior%20research%20economist%20at%20the%20Center%20for%20Retirement%20Research%20at%20Boston%20College%2C%20says%20people%20are%20addressing%20both%20by%20simply%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.businessinsider.com%2Fretirement-crisis-blackrock-letter-boomers-work-longer-employer-age-discrimination-2024-6%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3Eworking%20longer%3C%2Fa%3E.%20Researchers%2C%20she%20says%2C%20have%20seen%20more%20people%20claim%20Social%20Security%20while%20they're%20still%20earning%20an%20income%20%E2%80%94%20something%20that%20used%20to%20be%20typical%20only%20of%20retirees.%20Of%20Americans%2065%20and%20older%2C%20nearly%2011%20million%2C%20or%20about%2019%25%2C%20are%20employed%2C%20and%20that%20number%20is%20projected%20to%20rise%20to%20nearly%2015%20million%20by%202032.%20Twenty%20years%20ago%2C%20just%20under%205%20million%20Americans%20over%2065%20were%20employed.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3ESchmidt%20straddles%20these%20scenarios.%20Before%20retirement%2C%20he%20changed%20jobs%20too%20often%20to%20properly%20build%20up%20a%20pension%20%E2%80%94%20something%20he%20didn't%20realize%20until%20it%20was%20too%20late.%20Now%20finances%20are%20tight.%20%26quot%3BIn%20that%20sense%2C%20retirement%20has%20been%20a%20letdown%20and%20a%20struggle%2C%26quot%3B%20he%20says.%20He%20and%20his%20husband%2C%20who%20hasn't%20yet%20retired%2C%20have%20watched%20their%20savings%20dip%20even%20as%20Schmidt%20contributes%20through%20his%20part-time%20work.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EDee%20Cascio%2C%20a%20counselor%20and%20retirement%20coach%20in%20Sterling%2C%20Virginia%2C%20says%20the%20growing%20urge%20to%20work%20in%20retirement%20points%20to%20a%20larger%20issue%3A%20Work%20fulfills%20a%20lot%20of%20needs%20that%20people%20don't%20know%20how%20to%20get%20elsewhere%2C%20including%20relationships%2C%20learning%2C%20identity%2C%20direction%2C%20stability%2C%20and%20a%20sense%20of%20order.%20The%20structure%20that%20work%20provides%20is%20hard%20to%20move%20away%20from%2C%20says%20Cascio%2C%20who%20is%2078%20and%20still%20practicing.%20%26quot%3BPeople%20think%20that%20this%20transition%20is%20a%20piece%20of%20cake%2C%20and%20it's%20not%2C%26quot%3B%20she%20says.%20%26quot%3BIt%20can%20feel%20like%20jumping%20off%20a%20cliff.%26quot%3B%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EIn%20an%20online%20survey%20conducted%20early%20this%20year%20by%20Mass%20Mutual%2C%20a%20majority%20of%20retirees%20said%20they'd%20become%20less%20stressed%20and%20more%20relaxed%20upon%20retirement%2C%20but%20as%20many%20as%20a%20third%20reported%20that%20they'd%20become%20unhappier.%20Research%20from%20the%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fhrsonline.isr.umich.edu%2Fsitedocs%2Fdatabook%2F%3Fpage%3D34%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3EHealth%20and%20Retirement%20Study%3C%2Fa%3E%20from%20the%20University%20of%20Michigan%20suggests%20that%20some%20of%20the%20negative%20effects%20people%20can%20experience%20in%20retirement%20are%20tied%20to%20lifestyle%20changes%20such%20as%20being%20less%20active%20and%20social%20in%20the%20absence%20of%20work.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EFor%20some%2C%20the%20solution%20is%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.businessinsider.com%2Fstill-working-past-retirement-age-never-been-burned-out-2024-6%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3Eto%20never%20give%20up%20work%3C%2Fa%3E.%20Schmidt%20feels%20that%20even%20if%20there%20had%20been%20no%20need%20for%20him%20to%20make%20money%20after%20retiring%2C%20he%20still%20would've%20sought%20out%20a%20part-time%20job.%20With%20it%2C%20%26quot%3BI%20don't%20feel%20useless%2C%26quot%3B%20he%20says.%20%26quot%3BI%20do%20work%20that%20feels%20like%20I'm%20really%20giving%20something%20to%20the%20community.%26quot%3B%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EBut%20returning%20to%20your%20old%20line%20of%20work%20is%20hardly%20the%20only%20way%20to%20stay%20emotionally%20and%20intellectually%20fulfilled%20in%20retirement.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Chr%3E%3Cp%3EThe%20idea%20that%20our%20personal%20worth%20is%20determined%20by%20how%20hard%20we%20work%20and%20how%20much%20money%20we%20make%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.businessinsider.com%2Fcareerist-corporate-ladder-decline-promotions-work-ethic-american-dream-2024-10%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3Eis%20deeply%20embedded%20in%20US%20work%20culture%3C%2Fa%3E.%20This%20%26quot%3BProtestant%20work%20ethic%26quot%3B%20puts%20the%20responsibility%20of%20attaining%20a%20good%20quality%20of%20life%20and%20well-being%20on%20the%20worker%20%E2%80%94%20if%20you%20don't%20have%20the%20time%20or%20resources%20for%20leisure%2C%20it's%20because%20you%20haven't%20earned%3Cem%3E%20%3C%2Fem%3Eit.%20Or%20as%20Schmidt's%20father%20put%20it%2C%20%26quot%3BYou're%20not%20worth%20anything%20if%20you're%20not%20working.%26quot%3B%20This%20pernicious%20way%20of%20thinking%20prevents%20people%20from%20seeing%20purpose%20or%20value%20in%20life%20that%20doesn't%20involve%20working%20for%20a%20paycheck.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EMeanwhile%2C%20more%20and%20more%20research%20suggests%20that%20a%20sense%20of%20purpose%20is%20a%20vital%20factor%20for%20health%20and%20happiness%2C%20especially%20in%20older%20age.%20%26quot%3BHigher%20purpose%20in%20life%20is%20associated%20with%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fdoi.org%2F10.1007%2Fs11886-019-1222-9%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3Ereduced%20risk%20of%20heart%20attacks%20and%20strokes%3C%2Fa%3E%2C%26quot%3B%20says%20Eric%20Kim%2C%20an%20assistant%20professor%20of%20psychology%20at%20the%20University%20of%20British%20Columbia.%20For%20adults%20older%20than%2050%2C%20it's%20also%20associated%20with%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fjamanetwork.com%2Fjournals%2Fjamapsychiatry%2Ffullarticle%2F2648692%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3Ebetter%20grip%20strength%20and%20faster%20walking%20speed%3C%2Fa%3E%2C%20better%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fdoi.org%2F10.1177%2F08901171211038545%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3Eoverall%20health%2C%20healthier%20habits%2C%20less%20loneliness%2C%20and%20a%20lower%20risk%20of%20depression%3C%2Fa%3E.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3ESo%20what%20%3Cem%3Edoes%20%3C%2Fem%3Epurpose%20outside%20a%20career%20look%20like%3F%20Paul%20Draper%20thinks%20he's%20figured%20it%20out.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EIn%20August%202023%2C%20six%20months%20before%20he%20was%20set%20to%20retire%20from%20his%20job%20as%20an%20enterprise-software%20product%20manager%2C%20Draper%2C%20now%2068%2C%20made%20a%20plan.%20He%20liked%20his%20job%20and%20felt%20satisfied%20leaving%20it%20behind%2C%20but%20he%20recognized%20he%20still%20had%20a%20lot%20of%20energy%20and%20wanted%20to%20learn%20new%20things%20and%20meet%20new%20people.%20He%20was%20already%20involved%20in%20volunteering%20%E2%80%94%20doing%20prison%20ministry%20and%20working%20with%20soup%20kitchens%20%E2%80%94%20but%20more%20than%20that%2C%20%26quot%3BI%20was%20interested%20in%20doing%20things%20that%20I%20didn't%20know%20anything%20about%2C%26quot%3B%20he%20says.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EDraper's%20first%20thought%20was%20to%20work%20at%20a%20hardware%20store.%20He%20was%20somewhat%20handy%20but%20wanted%20to%20learn%20more%20about%20home%20repair.%20So%20he%20did.%20He%20got%20a%20part-time%20job%20at%20his%20local%20big-box%20hardware%20store%20handling%20doors%2C%20windows%2C%20and%20staircases.%20%26quot%3BThat%20was%20great%2C%26quot%3B%20he%20says%2C%20%26quot%3Bbecause%20all%20of%20a%20sudden%20I%20had%20to%20learn%20a%20lot%26quot%3B%20to%20be%20able%20to%20answer%20customers'%20questions%20and%20solve%20their%20problems.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EThe%20job%20was%20never%20meant%20to%20be%20a%20forever%20thing.%20After%2010%20months%2C%20it%20began%20to%20feel%20more%20monotonous%20and%20less%20like%20a%20learning%20opportunity%2C%20so%20Draper%20decided%20to%20move%20on.%20He%20plans%20to%20replicate%20that%20experience%20and%20pursue%20other%20areas%20of%20work%20he's%20fascinated%20by.%20%26quot%3BThere's%20a%20company%20in%20my%20area%20that%20builds%20continuous%20transmissions%20for%20bicycles%20and%20e-bikes%2C%26quot%3B%20he%20says.%20%26quot%3BI%20just%20want%20to%20intern%20there.%26quot%3B%20His%20dream%20role%2C%20however%2C%20is%20to%20lead%20city%20tours%20on%20Segways.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3ESince%20Draper%20isn't%20worried%20about%20needing%20an%20income%2C%20he%20can%20focus%20on%20learning.%20%26quot%3BThere%20are%20a%20million%20fun%20things%20to%20do%2C%20but%2099%25%20of%20them%20are%20unsustainable%20to%20do%20as%20a%20career%2C%26quot%3B%20he%20says.%20He%20views%20retirement%20as%20his%20opportunity%20to%20experiment%20with%20that%2099%25%20without%20worrying%20about%20achievement%2C%20a%20career%2C%20and%20the%20general%20hustle.%20Plus%2C%20he%20says%20it's%20been%20fairly%20easy%20to%20find%20these%20gigs.%20%26quot%3BI%20have%20found%20that%20there's%20a%20lot%20of%20employers%20that%20love%20retirees%2C%26quot%3B%20he%20says.%20%26quot%3BOne%2C%20because%20they're%20good%20with%20people.%20Two%2C%20because%20they're%20very%20reliable%20for%20the%20time%20that%20they%20have%20them%2C%20and%20they're%20calm%2C%20and%20they%20work%20well%20with%20other%20employees.%26quot%3B%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3ECascio%20has%20found%20that%20when%20helping%20clients%20bring%20purpose%20back%20into%20their%20lives%20in%20retirement%2C%20it%20can%20help%20to%20think%20about%20the%20%26quot%3Bsix%20arenas%20of%20life%26quot%3B%3A%20work%2C%20relationships%2C%20leisure%2C%20personal%20growth%2C%20finances%2C%20and%20health.%20A%20lot%20of%20people%20have%20drawn%20their%20sense%20of%20purpose%20or%20identity%20from%20work%2C%20and%20they%20might%20want%20to%20continue%20doing%20so%20through%20jobs%20or%20volunteering%20in%20retirement%2C%20she%20says.%20But%20any%20of%20these%20arenas%20can%20be%20a%20source%20of%20purpose.%20%26quot%3BIf%20you%20haven't%20attended%20to%20your%20health%20and%20that's%20something%20you%20want%20to%20improve%20in%20retirement%2C%20that%20can%20become%20a%20purpose%2C%26quot%3B%20she%20says.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3ESome%20activities%20can%20provide%20purpose%20in%20several%20of%20those%20areas.%20Draper's%20various%20odd%20jobs%20mean%20that%20he's%20more%20physically%20active%20than%20he%20would%20be%20if%20he%20stayed%20at%20home%2C%20and%20he's%20constantly%20meeting%20new%20people.%20%26quot%3BI've%20heard%20of%20people's%20circles%20closing%20up%2C%20but%20I'm%20finding%20I%20interact%20with%20more%20people%2C%20and%20on%20a%20regular%20basis%2C%26quot%3B%20he%20says.%20Both%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov%2Fpmc%2Farticles%2FPMC9858722%2F%23%3A~%3Atext%3DHowever%252C%2520engaging%2520in%2520social%2520activities%2520that%2520involve%2520the%2520relationships%2520of%2520the%2520older%2520adults%2520with%2520others%2520in%2520their%2520environment%2520improves%2520the%2520health%252C%2520well%252Dbeing%252C%2520and%2520happiness%2520of%2520the%2520older%2520adults%2520and%2520reduces%2520the%2520risks%2520associated%2520with%2520living%2520alone.%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3Egreater%20social%20interaction%3C%2Fa%3E%20and%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov%2Fpmc%2Farticles%2FPMC9151514%2F%23%3A~%3Atext%3DTheir%2520results%2520indicate%2Cestimated%2520well%252Dbeing.%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3Eincreased%20physical%20activity%3C%2Fa%3E%20are%20associated%20with%20happier%20and%20healthier%20aging.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EKim%20says%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.businessinsider.com%2Fexercise-for-healthy-aging-longevity-strength-training-personal-trainer-2024-8%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3Eretirees%20who%20aren't%20exercising%3C%2Fa%3E%2C%20socializing%2C%20or%20pursuing%20a%20sense%20of%20purpose%20may%20have%20self-limiting%20beliefs%20and%20pessimistic%20views%20of%20aging.%20%26quot%3BI've%20met%20people%20who%20will%20say%2C%20'I'm%20X%20years%20old%2C%20and%20people%20who%20are%20this%20age%20don't%20really%20exercise%20anymore%2C'%26quot%3B%20regardless%20of%20whether%20their%20bodies%20are%20capable%2C%20he%20says.%20Sometimes%20older%20adults%20have%20to%20first%20overcome%20the%20idea%20that%20because%20they%20are%20older%20they%20are%20limited.%20A%20well-known%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fpubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov%2F12150226%2F%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3E2002%20study%3C%2Fa%3E%20%E2%80%94%20and%20much%20follow-up%20research%20%E2%80%94%20found%20that%20people%20with%20more%20positive%20views%20of%20aging%20lived%20longer%20than%20those%20with%20more%20negative%20views.%20Kim%20says%20it%20can%20be%20tough%20to%20surmount%20those%20limiting%20beliefs%2C%20especially%20in%20a%20society%20where%20aging%20is%20seen%20as%20something%20to%20be%20avoided.%20In%20reality%2C%20there's%20no%20expiration%20date%20for%20finding%20new%20sources%20of%20fulfillment.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EOf%20course%2C%20some%20people%20are%20perfectly%20happy%20with%20a%20leisure-filled%20retirement.%20%26quot%3BIf%20you're%20only%20golfing%20and%20watching%20TV%20and%20you%20don't%20feel%20like%20there's%20anything%20missing%20in%20your%20life%2C%20you're%20completely%20happy%2C%20then%20I%20wouldn't%20go%20and%20say%20there%20is%20a%20psychological%20reason%20why%20you%20need%20to%20go%20and%20volunteer%20for%20a%20cause%20you%20care%20about%2C%26quot%3B%20says%20Yochai%20Shavit%2C%20the%20director%20of%20research%20at%20the%20Stanford%20Center%20on%20Longevity.%20If%20you%20live%20a%20life%20of%20leisure%20but%20are%20still%20bored%2C%20or%20if%20you're%20ignoring%20a%20sense%20of%20discontentment%2C%20that's%20when%20the%20trouble%20starts.%20%26quot%3BThe%20risk%20I%20see%20is%20that%20people%20brush%20aside%20those%20feelings%2C%26quot%3B%20he%20says.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EThere's%20no%20%26quot%3Bone%20size%20fits%20all%26quot%3B%20formula%20to%20retirement%2C%20but%20experts%20like%20Shavit%20hope%20that%20more%20people%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.businessinsider.com%2F95-year-old-superager-longevity-tips-healthy-aging-golf-volunteer-2024-11%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3Eapproach%20retirement%3C%2Fa%3E%20with%20the%20understanding%20that%20they%20still%20have%20the%20ability%20%E2%80%94%20and%20often%20the%20time%20%E2%80%94%20to%20find%20meaning%20and%20fulfillment.%20Don't%20fall%20into%20the%20trap%20of%20thinking%20that%20%26quot%3Bboredom%20is%20a%20'natural'%20part%20of%20retirement%20and%20having%20aches%2C%20both%20internally%20and%20physically%2C%20is%20just%20a%20part%20of%20growing%20old%2C%26quot%3B%20Shavit%20says.%20They're%20not%2C%20and%20they%20don't%20have%20to%20be.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Chr%3E%3Cp%3E%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.businessinsider.com%2Fauthor%2Fhannah-seo%5C%22%20target%3D%